title: For Sale:   FEG Hungarian SA-85M KASSNAR Import AK-47...Reduced!
postcontent:
In 1986 Kassnar Imports in Harrisburg, Pa., obtained a waiver from the State Department's munitions list to import 7,000 AKM-type semiautomatic only Kalashnikovs from Hungary. Some say, that someone screwed up big time with the approval, as Hungary was not on the short list of importers.

To make a long story short, these small batch of Hungarian FEG AKMs are said to be one of the best and most accurate AKs ever imported into the country. Only 4,000 underfolder and 3,000 stock Aks were ever imported in 1986, that's it!

I own two so I am putting one up for grabs. This one is in great shape with only two mags through it as I was told. The handguard has the nics on each side due to the underfolder edges touching when folded and some handling marks from it's 26 years. 

There was a lot more to Pre-ban Kassnar FeGs (Femaru Fegyvar es Gepgyar in Budapest). The SA-85M AKM is a civilian copy of their AK63 AKM machine gun. 

It's great to have a nice AK that you don't have worry about the stupid communist 922r section. 

This is truly a rare piece and is becoming harder to come by.

Thanks

title: For Sale:  How to spot a scam ad
postcontent:
Here's a couple tips to help you spot a scam ad.  Armslist moderators, I really hope you can make an article like this a sticky that appears at the top of every section.

1) Listing does not specify a city, only state.  Not a guarantee of a scam ad, but I find that these tend to be scams much more than listings in a specific city/region.  Most real sellers want you to know what region they're in so they can avoid wasting time talking to people who are too far away.

2) Identical listing appears in multiple states, pretending to be located in each state.  Hint: you can click "Listings by this user" and see how many different states they're trying to sell in, if they've used the same account for each one.  

3) Price is way under what it should be.  $800 Colt Pythons, etc.  Too good to be true, usually is.

4) Search on other gun selling web sites for the same model, and you find identical pictures from a listing there.  Very suspicious if the seller on on the other site isn't in the same state.  This one I consider a dead giveaway.  Scammers will steal good photos from other listings and around the internet.  Real Sellers:  when you take photographs, be smart and include something in the photo that makes it harder for someone else to rip it off, like the phone number or email address that you are using for your listing, the date, city/location where it's being offered.  

5) You email the seller, and there's something wrong about the way they convey themselves.  The words they use don't sound like the way real people write or talk.  They're supposedly in state, but won't meet you face to face. They say they're in another state than where their ad says they're located, and for some reason aren't willing to wait until they return home to do a FTF deal, or they say they "just moved".  They act like you're ready to send them money right now, without any discussion or meeting, etc.  They can't answer basic questions about the gun, like when they acquired it, etc.

If you spot an ad that you think is a scam, flag it!

title: For Sale:  RARE Randall Gen. Curtis E. LeMay 1911 45acp
postcontent: Any avid 1911 lover who knows about the history of these beautiful guns knows that Randall played a huge role in modernizing these fine firearms into what we know and love today. As the first company to produce commercially available 1911's in stainless steel, Randall Firearms has sealed a spot in history. With a total production of less than 10,000 firearms in it's entire existence, Randall 1911's are some of the most sought after and coveted collectors pieces out there. This particula model is one of the rarest produced by Randall (only 293 ever made). Here's a little bit of history on this particular model: THE CURTIS E. LeMAY 4-STAR PISTOLS In 1984, Randall expanded its line with the introduction of a true compact .45 auto, which was designed by Air Force General Curtis E. LeMay. Among his many accomplishments, LeMay had been responsible for establishing the Air Force’s Marksmanship Training Unit. When LeMay created his pistol design, he intended it to be used by members of the Strategic Air Force Command. The general initially tried to have the diminutive .45 produced by Colt. But, that never occurred. As it happened, Art Hanke, who was the head of manufacturing and engineering for Randall, was a personal friend of General LeMay. It was through this liaison that Randall Firearms Company came to produce the LeMay model line of pistols. The A331, which featured a flat top slide and Millett Low-Profile adjustable rear sight. The top of the slide was milled deeply so the rear sight would sit low enough to preclude its catching on clothing when drawn. There were 293 of this model produced in a serial number range of RF02010C through RF03169C. The first LeMay A331 was made on March 1, 1984, and the last one was completed on October 23rd of that same year. Now that you know that, let me tell you a little bit about this particular firearm. It's 100% factory original and in excellent condition. This handgun is not unfired, but pretty much flawless (as you can see from the pictures). I do not have the box or paperwork, just what you see in the pictures. Don't let this beauty get away. You never know when (or even if) you'll see another.

This pistol retains close to 90% of the early stunning Colt high polish mirror finish that was abruptly halted in 1912 after the 1911 went Into full production. It also retains nearly all fire blue on the trigger and bright vivid case color on the hammer. This gun is all correct and a fantastic collectors item.
